      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Silk is composed of natural fibroin proteins with a charged amino acid structure that actively attracts water molecules, allowing them to evaporate quickly across the fiber's surface for effective wicking. In contrast, polyester is synthesized from long hydrocarbon polymer chains that are non-polar and hydrophobic, causing sweat to bead up rather than spread or evaporate efficiently. This fundamental chemical difference means protein fibers facilitate moisture loss better than synthetic polymeric fibers, which instead trap moisture against the skin until it dries via external airflow.",
